# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electromagnetic-interference
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Like earlier cellular systems, 5G networks divide service areas into smaller zones called cells, which are served by fixed cell sites.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Compatible devices connect by radio to local base stations, which are linked to an operator's core network and to external networks such as the Internet through backhaul connections.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G can be deployed using low-band, mid-band, and high-band radio spectrum, with coverage and performance depending heavily on the frequencies used, network design, congestion, and device capabilities.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Compared with 4G, 5G is designed to provide higher data rates, greater network capacity, lower latency, improved support for dense device deployments, and more flexible network management.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Actual user speeds are typically much lower than peak values and vary by operator, location, spectrum band, signal quality, and network load.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G is used for mobile broadband, fixed wireless access, private and industrial networks, and machine-type communications.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Its standards support features such as network slicing, edge computing, non-public networks, and ultra-reliable low-latency services, although these capabilities are not present in every deployment.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The rollout of 5G has required new spectrum allocations and upgrades to radio access, transport, and core-network infrastructure.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] It has also raised issues involving deployment cost, energy use, vendor security, and public claims about radio-frequency health effects.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G is being deployed alongside 4G networks and is expected to coexist with them for many years.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In 2008, NASA and the Machine-to-Machine Intelligence Corporation (M2Mi) conducted nanosatellite communication studies that influenced early next-generation network concepts.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In 2012, New York University established NYU Wireless, a research center focused on millimeter-wave communication.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The same year, the University of Surrey founded the 5G Innovation Centre, funded by £35 million from public and industry partners including Huawei and Samsung.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Also in 2012, the European Union launched the *Mobile and Wireless Communications Enablers for the Twenty-Twenty Information Society (METIS)* project to align emerging network research with international standardization.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In 2013, the ITU-R Working Party 5D began studies on *IMT-2020*, later formalized as the 5G standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] During the same period, major firms such as Samsung Electronics, NTT Docomo, and Huawei conducted early trials.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Samsung tested a prototype achieving more than 1 Gbit/s across 2 km using 8 × 8 MIMO antennas.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] NTT Docomo received a government award at CEATEC for high-speed network development, while Huawei announced a US$600 million program to advance mobile network technology.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] On April 3, 2019, South Korea launched its national network, the first full commercial deployment.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Hours later, Verizon began limited service in select U.S. cities.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In June 2019, Globe Telecom introduced the Philippines' first next-generation network, and in December 2019, AT&T launched a consumer service in the United States that expanded nationwide during 2020.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Commercial 5G deployment expanded rapidly through 2020.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Beyond public mobile networks, it was also adopted in private industrial and enterprise systems, including operation in unlicensed spectrum (NR-U) and licensed non-public networks (NPNs).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Private 5G networks became important for Industry 4.0 automation and smart manufacturing.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Early rollouts used non-standalone (NSA) mode—with 4G cores—before networks transitioned to standalone (SA) mode with dedicated 5G cores.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] South Korea’s 2019 rollout used equipment from Samsung, Ericsson, and Nokia; LG U Plus also deployed Huawei hardware.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Samsung supplied most of the roughly 86,000 sites, while SK Telecom, KT Corporation, and LG U Plus concentrated coverage in major cities using the 3.5 GHz band under NSA operation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Reported download speeds averaged 200–400 Mbit/s, and subscriptions grew from about 260,000 to 4.7 million during 2019.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Following these early deployments, T-Mobile US launched the first nationwide standalone network in 2020.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Ericsson projected that by the mid-2020s, 5G networks would reach about 65 percent of the global population.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Major suppliers of 5G radio and core systems included Altiostar, Cisco Systems, Datang Telecom/Fiberhome, Ericsson, Huawei, Nokia, Qualcomm, Samsung, and ZTE.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Huawei was estimated to hold about 70 percent of global 5G base stations by 2023.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] By 2022, network speeds in many regions had stabilized, and operators began testing 5.5G upgrades to improve capacity and latency.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] By the early 2020s, large-scale commercial 5G networks were active across most developed markets, and rollout in developing regions was still accelerating.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Small cells are low-power radio nodes that extend network capacity in dense or indoor areas.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] They operate over short distances, typically a few dozen to a few hundred metres, and are used to maintain coverage for mmWave signals.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Massive multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) systems use large antenna arrays to increase capacity and spectral efficiency.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] They extend conventional MIMO by serving multiple users simultaneously and steering signals toward them to reduce interference.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Beamforming directs radio energy toward specific users.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In analogue beamforming, antenna outputs are combined to focus signal power in one direction.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Digital beamforming transmits data streams across multiple layers to improve signal strength and reliability.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Non-orthogonal multiple access assigns different power levels to users sharing the same frequency resources to improve spectral efficiency.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G NR uses polar codes for control channels and low-density parity-check codes (LDPC) for data channels, replacing the turbo codes used in 4G.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Research has explored the use of 5G mmWave networks for wireless power transfer.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Studies using wavelengths between 1 mm and 10 mm remain experimental.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The 5G core (5GC) is a service-oriented, software-defined system that separates control and user planes and supports flexible deployment.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] It replaces the 4G Evolved Packet Core with modular, software-based network functions.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) enable software-based configuration, scaling, and management of networks.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Together with network slicing, these technologies support applications such as the Internet of things, connected vehicles, and industrial automation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Service-based architecture (SBA) integrates SDN and NFV principles and replaces the 4G EPC framework with modular network functions that communicate through RESTful APIs.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Each function registers with a network repository function (NRF), which enables independent scaling and interoperability.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Each network function performs a defined role within the 5G core, replacing or extending elements from the 4G EPC.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G networks use multiple parts of the radio spectrum.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] They operate across three main frequency ranges—low, mid, and high bands—which balance speed, coverage, and signal quality differently.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Between 2016 and 2019, regulators in many regions, including the United States and the European Union, reallocated large sections of spectrum for 5G through auctions and new licensing rules.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] By 2019, more than 50 countries had assigned or planned to assign 5G frequencies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In 3GPP Release 16, the standard added 5G NR-U, allowing operation in both unlicensed and licensed spectrum.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Low- and mid-band 5G provide broad coverage and reliable indoor reception.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] High-band signals weaken rapidly and may lose over 100 dB when passing through common building materials.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Operators use beamforming antennas, small cells, and signal repeaters to extend range and improve indoor coverage.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Technologies such as License Assisted Access (LAA) and LTE-WLAN Aggregation (LWA) let mobile networks share unlicensed spectrum with Wi-Fi.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Cloud-based RAN systems and dense small-cell layouts help narrow the performance gap between cellular and Wi-Fi links.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The ITU-R defines three main application areas for 5G: enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB), ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC), and massive machine-type communications (mMTC).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] These categories describe the main uses of 5G: faster mobile connections (eMBB), highly reliable and responsive communication (URLLC), and large-scale links between machines (mMTC).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] By 2020, eMBB was widely deployed, while URLLC and mMTC were still in development.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB) provides much faster internet and higher capacity than 4G.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] It supports intensive data use in busy areas such as city centres, stadiums, and transport hubs.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Ultra-reliable low-latency communications (URLLC) are designed for time-critical applications such as factory automation, remote medical procedures, and traffic systems.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Shorter transmission delays improve precision and reliability.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Massive machine-type communications (mMTC) connect large numbers of low-power devices such as sensors and meters.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] These networks underpin the Internet of things (IoT) by allowing machines to exchange data autonomously in industry, transport, and urban systems.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G is used in transport, manufacturing, and energy systems that require constant, low-latency communication.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The 5G Automotive Association develops vehicle-to-everything (C-V2X) standards that allow cars to exchange safety information with nearby vehicles and infrastructure.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Drones and autonomous vehicles use 5G for navigation, remote control, and real-time data transmission.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Low-latency connections also enable digital twin models—virtual copies of machines or buildings that show real-time performance data used for monitoring and maintenance.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G extends to public safety, broadband access, and media delivery.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Emergency services use it for live video, data, and reliable push-to-talk communication.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Fixed wireless access (FWA) provides home and business broadband using 5G radio links instead of wired connections, especially in rural areas where laying cables is costly.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G Broadcast trials in Europe show that local 5G networks can deliver live television and radio to many devices simultaneously without using mobile data plans.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Voice over NR (VoNR) allows phone calls to be made over 5G's internet-based network, similar to Voice over LTE (VoLTE) on 4G.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G can deliver much higher data rates than 4G, up to ten times faster.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Theoretical peak download speeds reach up to 20 Gbit/s.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In practice, average 5G download speeds in the United States have been measured at about 186 Mbit/s by T-Mobile, while South Korea in 2022 led globally with averages near 430 Mbit/s.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G networks are also designed to provide much greater total capacity and efficiency than 4G, with up to a hundredfold projected increase.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The most widely deployed version, sub-6 GHz (mid-band) 5G, provides speeds of roughly 10–1000 Mbit/s with wider reach than mmWave bands.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] C-Band (n77/n78) was introduced in the U.S. in 2022, though activation by Verizon and AT&T was briefly delayed due to FAA safety concerns.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The highest 5G speed measured in a deployed network is 5.9 Gbit/s (2023).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Low-band frequencies such as n5 cover larger areas per cell but deliver lower data rates of around 5–250 Mbit/s.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Typical *air latency* for 5G is around 8–12 ms, excluding retransmissions and handovers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Verizon reported about 30 ms latency in early deployments.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Edge servers located near base stations can reduce round-trip time to roughly 14 ms and minimize jitter to about 1.8 ms.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Latency increases substantially during handovers, ranging from 50 to 150 ms depending on network conditions.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Ongoing research focuses on reducing these interruptions by adjusting handover margins and time-to-trigger parameters.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G uses adaptive modulation and coding schemes (MCS) to maintain a low block error rate (BLER).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] When the error rate exceeds a threshold, the system automatically switches to a lower MCS to prioritize reliability over speed.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The range of 5G varies with transmit power, frequency, and interference.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] High-frequency mmWave bands (e.g., n258) have a shorter range than mid-band (n78), which in turn has a shorter range than low-band (n5).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Operators use network simulation and drive testing to measure the actual range and coverage of these bands, as real-world performance can differ from marketing claims.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The term 5G was first associated with the International Telecommunication Union's IMT-2020 standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] It defines peak download and upload rates of 20 and 10 Gbit/s.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The 3rd Generation Partnership Project (3GPP) later proposed its 5G New Radio (NR) technology for IMT-2020.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Early FR1 deployments reusing 4G infrastructure (non-standalone mode) have been reported to provide 15–50 percent higher throughput than advanced 4G networks under favorable conditions.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G networks can operate in Non-Standalone (NSA) mode using existing LTE infrastructure or Standalone (SA) mode using a dedicated 5G Core (5GC) network.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Other organizations also contribute to 5G standards.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The DECT-2020 specification defines DECT NR+, a non-cellular, mesh-based radio system recognized by ITU as part of 5G.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The IEEE defines standards for wired links between the remote radio unit (RRU) and the baseband unit (BBU).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5Gi was developed in India by IIT Madras, IIT Hyderabad, the Telecommunications Standards Development Society India (TSDSI) and the Centre of Excellence in Wireless Technology (CEWiT).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] It extends 5G coverage in rural and remote areas through low-mobility large-cell (LMLC) configurations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5Gi was merged in April 2022 into the global 5G NR standard in 3GPP Release 17.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In the Internet of things (IoT), 3GPP defines the evolution of NB-IoT and eMTC to support low-power wide-area applications such as connected sensors and meters.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 3GPP standards also define advanced communication services for voice and connected devices.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 3GPP defines Voice over NR as a technology that enables native, high-quality voice over a 5G Standalone network through the 5G System Architecture.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Unlike early 5G Non-Standalone deployments that relied on Evolved Packet System Fallback, VoNR integrates directly with the IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS) used in VoLTE.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] It uses NAS protocols to establish high-priority QoS flows that support URLLC requirements for voice traffic.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Support for 5G Standalone is a prerequisite for VoNR.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] VoNR benefits from the enhanced security architecture of the 5G Core network, including improved subscriber identity protection.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] VoNR delivers superior audio quality through the Enhanced Voice Services (EVS) codec, which must adhere to rigorous terminal acoustic requirements and standardized testing procedures.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Most phones released since 2023 (such as the iPhone 15 series and newer flagship devices) support VoNR, but availability depends on carrier enablement in specific areas.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 3GPP also defines non-terrestrial networks (NTN) that use satellites and airborne platforms to provide coverage where ground networks are impractical.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G-Advanced, also known as 5.5G or 5G-A, is defined in 3GPP Release 18 as a transition between 5G and 6G.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] It adds features for more efficient spectrum use, lower energy demand, and higher reliability.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The release introduces AI- and ML-based network management, extended-reality services, and communication support for autonomous systems.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Release 18 specifies improved time-synchronization methods independent of the GNSS and built-in geolocation functions.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] It extends non-terrestrial support to satellite and airborne communication.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G Reduced Capability (RedCap) in 3GPP Release 17 is designed to bridge the gap between high-performance 5G devices and low-power IoT technologies such as LTE-M and NB-IoT.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] It was created to address use cases between Enhanced Mobile Broadband (eMBB), Ultra-Reliable Low-Latency Communications (URLLC), and Massive Machine-Type Communication (mMTC) technologies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The Global Mobile Suppliers Association (GSA) compiled the first database of 5G-compatible products, listing 23 manufacturers and 33 models across categories such as smartphones, hotspots, and customer-premises equipment.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Later surveys recorded more than one hundred announced products from over fifty vendors.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Early 5G modem chipsets were released by Intel, MediaTek, Qualcomm, and Samsung, followed by additional platforms in subsequent product generations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The Samsung Galaxy S10 5G was among the first smartphones to support 5G networks.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Other early 5G models included the Nokia 8.3 5G, designed for operation across low- to mid-band frequencies; the Google Pixel 5 and Pixel 4a (5G); and Apple's iPhone 12 series, the company's first generation with 5G capability.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] By the early 2020s, most high-end smartphones featured 5G capability, while some consumer devices still lack full support.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] As a result, the practical benefits for mid range phone users have been modest, and 5G adoption has lagged behind expectations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In 2019, the European Commission and the European Union Agency for Cybersecurity (ENISA) warned that 5G networks could expand potential attack surfaces for state actors, recommending diversification of suppliers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Nokia and Ericsson are the only European manufacturers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Researchers from ETH Zurich and partner universities found weaknesses in the 5G authentication process that could expose users to new security risks.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] They concluded that the system was still immature and that its higher data capacity could increase exposure to attacks.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] A 2022 study identified a design flaw in the Evolved Packet System (EPS) that could affect device behavior during network switching.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Growth of the Internet of things increases the number of devices connected through 5G.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] IoT Analytics estimated growth from about 7 billion devices in 2018 to over 21 billion by 2025, raising exposure to DDoS attacks, cryptojacking, and other cyberattacks.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Concerns about espionage and data access have influenced national policies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The United States, Australia, and the United Kingdom have restricted or banned Chinese-made equipment.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] A 2012 report by the United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence concluded that equipment from Huawei and ZTE could pose national-security risks.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Later assessments by U.S. intelligence agencies warned that Huawei products could allow covert data access.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In 2022, the FBI reported that Huawei equipment near U.S. military bases could interfere with nuclear communications.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Huawei and the Chinese government deny the allegations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Analysts note that China's National Security Law could require companies to provide data to authorities if requested.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In 2020, the United States Department of State launched The Clean Network initiative to promote data privacy and security among allied nations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] By year-end, more than 60 countries and 200 telecommunications companies had joined, including most NATO, EU, and OECD members.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Some 5G bands, such as n258 at 26 GHz, are close to frequencies used for passive remote sensing by weather and Earth observation satellites, including water vapor measurements at 23.8 GHz.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Interference with satellite observations could reduce the accuracy of numerical weather prediction models and affect sectors such as commercial aviation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Navy warned that out-of-band emissions from 5G transmissions near 24 GHz could degrade forecasts by up to 30 %.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The 2019 World Radiocommunication Conference set an interim limit of −33 dBW until 2027, followed by −39 dBW.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The World Meteorological Organization (WMO) and European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts (ECMWF) warned that these limits could reduce forecast reliability.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In 2021–2022, the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) warned that some 5G signals could interfere with aircraft radar altimeters, which operate at 4.2–4.4 GHz, while new 5G services use 3.7–4.0 GHz.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Europe uses lower frequencies (3.4–3.8 GHz), reducing the risk.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Some 5G allocations overlap with frequencies used by C band satellite communication systems.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Interference can occur when networks operate in 3.3–3.6 GHz, near satellite reception at 3.4–4.2 GHz Mitigation uses low-noise block downconverters and waveguide filters.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] 5G and Wi-Fi 6E share the 6 GHz band, which enables efficient spectrum use but requires coordination to prevent interference.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Both operate under unlicensed conditions in the US and EU, supporting NR-U and Wi-Fi 6E technologies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Analysts note that marketing of 5G has often overstated its capabilities.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Common concerns include limited user benefits, short range of mmWave signals, and rebranding of non-5G improvements as 5G.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] A 2020 survey by McKinsey & Company found that operators identified few immediately profitable use cases.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Consumer surveys show mixed attitudes, with skepticism about marketing claims and uneven coverage in early deployments.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Industry groups and network operators state that 5G enables faster speeds and lower latency, though results depend on infrastructure rollout and available spectrum.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In contrast to the initial excitement about the prospects, many firms striving for deployment have encountered reality, users are not eager to upgrade the technology.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Five years after its launch, a majority of users have yet to transition to the new standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Public concern about the effects of wireless signals predates 5G technology.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Similar concerns were raised about earlier mobile standards in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), "exposure to intense, direct amounts of non-ionizing radiation may result in tissue damage due to heat.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Some critics argue that existing exposure limits are too lenient or influenced by industry lobbying.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Claims that the use of 5G mobile networks can cause cancer are unsupported by scientific evidence.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Several books making unverified claims about wireless health effects have been published.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] One, by Joseph Mercola, alleged links to ADHD, heart disease, and brain cancer.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Mercola was criticized for promoting misinformation during the COVID-19 pandemic and warned by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for selling unapproved COVID-19 cures.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] According to *The New York Times*, controversy regarding 5G health effects partly originated from an unpublished 2000 report by physicist Bill P.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Curry for the Broward County School Board, which incorrectly concluded that higher-frequency microwaves are absorbed more deeply by the brain.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Later analyses showed that this was a misunderstanding of *in vitro* research results.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Experts noted that millimeter-wave frequencies used by 5G cannot penetrate the skin or reach internal organs.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In a 2019 article, the same newspaper reported that RT America promoted claims linking 5G to diseases such as brain cancer, infertility, and Alzheimer's disease.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The network aired several such programs in 2019, later cited by numerous blogs and websites.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In 2019, cities such as Brussels and Geneva temporarily halted 5G rollouts pending radiation assessments.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The Swiss Telecommunications Association stated that studies had not demonstrated adverse health effects from 5G exposure.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Similar debates occurred in the Netherlands, the United States, and the United Kingdom, where some municipalities briefly delayed deployments or issued precautionary statements.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The Food and Drug Administration maintains that existing exposure limits for cellphone radiofrequency energy are sufficient to protect public health.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Low-level electromagnetic fields (EMF) can have measurable biological effects in plants and animals, but research remains inconclusive about health risks to humans.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] A 2019 meta-analysis found that while many *in vitro* and *in vivo* studies detected biological responses to radiofrequency exposure, the evidence did not establish health risks.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The rollout of 5G technology began during the COVID-19 pandemic, prompting conspiracy theories that linked 5G to the pandemic.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] These claims led to arson attacks on telecom masts in parts of Europe, including the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and Italy.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In the United Kingdom, at least 61 mobile masts were reportedly set on fire.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] During the early months of the pandemic, Australian anti-lockdown protesters carried anti-5G signs, later connected to broader conspiracy groups.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The second claims that 5G causes COVID-19.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Some versions claim the pandemic hid illnesses blamed on 5G, while others suggest COVID-19 began in Wuhan, one of the first cities with early 5G rollout.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] The marketing of pre-5G technologies refers to the promotion of enhanced 4G networks as precursors or alternatives to 5G.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] Before and during early 5G deployment, some mobile network operators used terms such as "pre-5G", "5G-ready", "4.5G", and "5G Evolution" for upgraded LTE Advanced or LTE Advanced Pro networks.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] These networks could use features such as carrier aggregation, 256-QAM, and 4×4 MIMO to increase data rates, but they did not use 5G NR, the radio access technology standardized for 5G networks.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] A notable example was 5G Evolution, introduced by AT&T in 2017 to market higher-speed LTE service.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] AT&T described the service as "a foundation for our evolution to 5G while the 5G standards are being finalized", but technology publications criticized the branding as misleading because the underlying network remained based on LTE technologies rather than 5G.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In 2019, Sprint sued AT&T, alleging that the 5G Evolution and "5GE" branding misled consumers into believing that they were receiving 5G service.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/5g] In 2020, the National Advertising Review Board recommended that AT&T stop using "5G Evolution" and related claims in advertising, finding that the terms were misleading; AT&T said it disagreed with the decision but would comply with the self-regulatory process.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] 802.11 is a set of IEEE standards that govern wireless networking transmission methods.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] They are commonly used today in their 802.11a, 802.11b, 802.11g, 802.11n, 802.11ac and 802.11ax versions to provide wireless connectivity in the home, office and some commercial establishments.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] 802.11b has a maximum raw data rate of 11 Mbit/s and uses the same CSMA/CA media access method defined in the original standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Due to the CSMA/CA protocol overhead, in practice the maximum 802.11b throughput that an application can achieve is about 5.9 Mbit/s using TCP and 7.1 Mbit/s using UDP.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] 802.11b products appeared on the market in mid-1999, since 802.11b is a direct extension of the DSSS (Direct-sequence spread spectrum) modulation technique defined in the original standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] The Apple iBook was the first mainstream computer sold with optional 802.11b networking.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Technically, the 802.11b standard uses complementary code keying (CCK) as its modulation technique, which uses a specific set of length 8 complementary codes that was originally designed for OFDM but was also suitable for use in 802.11b because of its low autocorrelation properties.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] The dramatic increase in throughput of 802.11b (compared to the original standard) along with simultaneous substantial price reductions led to the rapid acceptance of 802.11b as the definitive wireless LAN technology as well as to the formation of the Wi-Fi Alliance.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] 802.11b devices suffer interference from other products operating in the 2.4 GHz band.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Devices operating in the 2.4 GHz range include: microwave ovens, Bluetooth devices, baby monitors and cordless telephones.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Interference issues and user density problems within the 2.4 GHz band have become a major concern and frustration for users.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] 802.11b is used in a point-to-multipoint configuration, wherein an access point communicates via an omnidirectional antenna with mobile clients within the range of the access point.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Typical range depends on the radio frequency environment, output power and sensitivity of the receiver.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Allowable bandwidth is shared across clients in discrete channels.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] A directional antenna focuses transmit and receive power into a smaller field which reduces interference and increases point-to-point range.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Designers of such installations who wish to remain within the law must however be careful about legal limitations on effective radiated power.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Some 802.11b cards operate at 11 Mbit/s, but scale back to 5.5, then to 2, then to 1 Mbit/s (also known as Adaptive Rate Selection) in order to decrease the rate of re-broadcasts that result from errors.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Note: Channel 14 is only allowed in Japan, Channels 12 & 13 are allowed in most parts of the world.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] IEEE 802.11y-2008 extended operation of 802.11a to the licensed 3.7 GHz band.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Increased power limits allow a range up to 5,000 m.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] As of 2009, it is only being licensed in the United States by the FCC.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Based on short guard interval; standard guard interval is ~10% slower.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Rates vary widely based on distance, obstructions, and interference.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] For single-user cases only, based on default guard interval which is 0.8 microseconds.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Since multi-user via OFDMA has become available for 802.11ax, these may decrease.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] Also, these theoretical values depend on the link distance, whether the link is line-of-sight or not, interferences and the multi-path components in the environment.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] The default guard interval is 0.8 microseconds.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11b] However, 802.11ax extended the maximum available guard interval to 3.2 microseconds, in order to support outdoor communications, where the maximum possible propagation delay is larger compared to Indoor environments.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] 802.11g is fully backward compatible with 802.11b, but coexistence of the two methods creates a significant performance penalty.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] 802.11g is the third modulation standard for wireless LANs.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] It works in the 2.4 GHz band (like 802.11b) but operates at a maximum raw data rate of 54 Mbit/s.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Using the CSMA/CA transmission scheme, 31.4 Mbit/s is the maximum net throughput possible for packets of 1500 bytes in size and a 54 Mbit/s wireless rate (identical to 802.11a core, except for some additional legacy overhead for backward compatibility).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] In practice, access points may not have an ideal implementation and may therefore not be able to achieve even 31.4 Mbit/s throughput with 1500 byte packets.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] 1500 bytes is the usual limit for packets on the Internet and therefore a relevant size to benchmark against.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Smaller packets give even lower theoretical throughput, down to 3 Mbit/s using 54 Mbit/s rate and 64 byte packets.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Also, the available throughput is shared between all stations transmitting, including the AP so both downstream and upstream traffic is limited to a shared total of 31.4 Mbit/s using 1500 byte packets and 54 Mbit/s rate.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] 802.11g hardware is fully backward compatible with 802.11b hardware.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Details of making b and g work well together occupied much of the lingering technical process.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] In an 802.11g network, however, the presence of a legacy 802.11b participant will significantly reduce the speed of the overall 802.11g network, as airtime needs to be managed by RTS/CTS transmissions and a "back off" mechanism.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Some 802.11g routers employ a back-compatible mode for 802.11b clients called 54g LRS (Limited Rate Support).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] The modulation scheme used in 802.11g is orthogonal frequency-division multiplexing (OFDM) copied from 802.11a with data rates of 6, 9, 12, 18, 24, 36, 48, and 54 Mbit/s, and reverts to CCK (like the 802.11b standard) for 5.5 and 11 Mbit/s and DBPSK/DQPSK+DSSS for 1 and 2 Mbit/s.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Even though 802.11g operates in the same frequency band as 802.11b, it can achieve higher data rates because of its better modulation from 802.11a.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Of the 52 OFDM subcarriers, 48 are for data and 4 are pilot subcarriers with a carrier separation of 0.3125 MHz (20 MHz/64).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Each of these subcarriers can be a BPSK, QPSK, 16-QAM or 64-QAM.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] The total bandwidth is 22 MHz with an occupied bandwidth of 16.6 MHz.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Symbol duration is 4 microseconds, which *includes* a guard interval of 0.8 microseconds.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] The actual generation and decoding of orthogonal components is done in baseband using DSP which is then upconverted to 2.4 GHz at the transmitter.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Each of the subcarriers could be represented as a complex number.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] The time domain signal is generated by taking an Inverse Fast Fourier transform (IFFT).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Correspondingly the receiver downconverts, samples at 20 MHz and does an FFT to retrieve the original coefficients.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] The advantages of using OFDM include reduced multipath effects in reception and increased spectral efficiency.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] The then-proposed 802.11g standard was rapidly adopted by consumers starting in January 2003, well before ratification, due to the desire for higher speeds and reductions in manufacturing costs.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] By mid-2003, most dual-band 802.11a/b products became dual-band/tri-mode, supporting a and b/g in a single mobile adapter card or access point.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Despite its major acceptance, 802.11g suffers from the same interference as 802.11b in the already crowded 2.4 GHz range.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Devices operating in this range include microwave ovens, Bluetooth devices, baby monitors, and digital cordless telephones, which can lead to interference issues.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Additionally, the success of the standard has caused usage/density problems related to crowding in urban areas.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] To prevent interference, there are only three non-overlapping usable channels in the U.S. and other countries with similar regulations (channels 1, 6, 11, with 25 MHz separation), and four in Europe (channels 1, 5, 9, 13, with only 20 MHz separation).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11g] Even with such separation, some interference due to side lobes exists, though it is considerably weaker.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Being the first Wi-Fi standard to introduce MIMO support, devices and systems which supported the 802.11n standard (or draft versions thereof) were sometimes referred to as MIMO Wi-Fi products, especially prior to the introduction of the next generation standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The use of MIMO-OFDM (orthogonal frequency division multiplexing) to increase the data rate while maintaining the same spectrum as 802.11a was first demonstrated by Airgo Networks.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] IEEE 802.11n-2009 is an amendment to the IEEE 802.11-2007 wireless-networking standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] They are commonly used today in their 802.11a, 802.11b, 802.11g, 802.11n, 802.11ac and 802.11ax versions to provide wireless connectivity in homes and businesses.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Development of 802.11n began in 2002, seven years before publication.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The 802.11n protocol is now Clause 20 of the published IEEE 802.11-2012 standard and subsequently renamed to clause 19 of the published IEEE 802.11-2020 standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] There were older proprietary implementations of MIMO and 40MHz channels such as Xpress, Super G and Nitro which were based upon 802.11g and 802.11a technology, but this was the first time it was standardized across all radio manufacturers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] MIMO is a technology that uses multiple antennas to coherently resolve more information than possible using a single antenna.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] One way it provides this is through spatial division multiplexing (SDM), which spatially multiplexes multiple independent data streams, transferred simultaneously within one spectral channel of bandwidth.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] MIMO SDM can significantly increase data throughput as the number of resolved spatial data streams is increased.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Each spatial stream requires a discrete antenna at both the transmitter and the receiver.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] In addition, MIMO technology requires a separate radio-frequency chain and analog-to-digital converter for each antenna, making it more expensive to implement than non-MIMO systems.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Channels operating with a width of 40 MHz are another feature incorporated into 802.11n; this doubles the channel width from 20 MHz in previous 802.11 PHYs to transmit data, and provides twice the PHY data rate available over a single 20 MHz channel.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] It can be enabled in the 5 GHz mode, or within the 2.4 GHz mode if there is knowledge that it will not interfere with any other 802.11 or non-802.11 (such as Bluetooth) system using the same frequencies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The MIMO architecture, together with the wider channels, offers increased physical transfer rate over standard 802.11a (5 GHz) and 802.11g (2.4 GHz).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The transmitter and receiver use precoding and postcoding techniques, respectively, to achieve the capacity of a MIMO link.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Precoding includes spatial beamforming and spatial coding, where spatial beamforming improves the received signal quality at the decoding stage.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Spatial coding can increase data throughput via spatial multiplexing and increase range by exploiting the spatial diversity, through techniques such as Alamouti coding.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The number of simultaneous data streams is limited by the minimum number of antennas in use on both sides of the link.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] However, the individual radios often further limit the number of spatial streams that may carry unique data.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The a × b : c notation helps identify what a given radio is capable of.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The first number (a) is the maximum number of transmit antennas or transmitting TF chains that can be used by the radio.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The second number (b) is the maximum number of receive antennas or receiving RF chains that can be used by the radio.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The third number (c) is the maximum number of data spatial streams the radio can use.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] For example, a radio that can transmit on two antennas and receive on three, but can only send or receive two data streams, would be 2 × 3 : 2.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Common configurations of 11n devices are 2 × 2 : 2, 2 × 3 : 2, and 3 × 2 : 2.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] All three configurations have the same maximum throughputs and features, and differ only in the amount of diversity the antenna systems provide.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] In addition, a fourth configuration, 3 × 3 : 3 is becoming common, which has a higher throughput, due to the additional data stream.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] If more antennas are used, then 802.11n can go up to 288 megabits per second in 20 MHz mode with four antennas, or 600 megabits per second in 40 MHz mode with four antennas and 400 ns guard interval.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Thus, network engineers installing an 802.11n network should strive to select routers and wireless clients with the most antennas possible (one, two, three or four as specified by the 802.11n standard) and try to make sure that the network's bandwidth will be satisfactory even on the 20 MHz mode.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Data rates up to 600 Mbit/s are achieved only with the maximum of four spatial streams using one 40 MHz-wide channel.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Various modulation schemes and coding rates are defined by the standard, which also assigns an arbitrary number to each; this number is the *modulation and coding scheme index*, or *MCS index*.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The table below shows the relationships between the variables that allow for the maximum data rate.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] GI (Guard Interval): Timing between symbols.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] 20 MHz channel uses an FFT of 64, of which: 56 OFDM subcarriers, 52 are for data and 4 are pilot tones with a carrier separation of 0.3125 MHz (20 MHz/64) (3.2 μs).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The total bandwidth is 20 MHz with an occupied bandwidth of 17.8 MHz.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Total symbol duration is 3.6 or 4 microseconds, which *includes* a guard interval of 0.4 (also known as short guard interval (SGI)) or 0.8 microseconds.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] PHY level data rate does not match user level throughput because of 802.11 protocol overheads, like the contention process, interframe spacing, PHY level headers (Preamble + PLCP) and acknowledgment frames.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The main media access control (MAC) feature that provides a performance improvement is aggregation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Frame aggregation is a process of packing multiple MSDUs or MPDUs together to reduce the overheads and average them over multiple frames, thereby increasing the user level data rate.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] A-MPDU aggregation requires the use of block acknowledgement or BlockAck, which was introduced in 802.11e and has been optimized in 802.11n.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] When 802.11g was released to share the band with existing 802.11b devices, it provided ways of ensuring backward compatibility between legacy and successor devices.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] 802.11n extends the coexistence management to protect its transmissions from legacy devices, which include 802.11g, 802.11b and 802.11a.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] PHY level protection: Transmissions using a 40 MHz channel in the presence of 802.11a or 802.11g clients require using CTS protection on both 20 MHz halves of the 40 MHz channel, to prevent interference with legacy devices.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] MAC level protection: An RTS/CTS frame exchange or CTS frame transmission at legacy rates can be used to protect subsequent 11n transmission.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] To achieve maximum output, a pure 802.11n 5 GHz network is recommended.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The 5 GHz band has substantial capacity due to many non-overlapping radio channels and less radio interference as compared to the 2.4 GHz band.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] An 802.11n-only network may be impractical for many users because they need to support legacy equipment that still is 802.11b/g only.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] In a mixed-mode system, an optimal solution would be to use a dual-radio access point and place the 802.11b/g traffic on the 2.4 GHz radio and the 802.11n traffic on the 5 GHz radio.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] This setup assumes that all the 802.11n clients are 5 GHz capable, which is not a requirement of the standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] 5 GHz is optional on Wi-Fi 4; quite some Wi-Fi 4 capable devices only support 2.4 GHz and there is no practical way to upgrade them to support 5 GHz.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Some enterprise-grade APs use **band steering** to send 802.11n clients to the 5 GHz band, leaving the 2.4 GHz band for legacy clients.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Band steering works by responding only to 5 GHz association requests and not the 2.4 GHz requests from dual-band clients.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The 2.4 GHz ISM band is fairly congested.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] With 802.11n, there is the option to double the bandwidth per channel to 40 MHz (fat channel) which results in slightly more than double the data rate.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] However, in North America, when in 2.4 GHz, enabling this option takes up to 82% of the unlicensed band.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] For example, channel 3 SCA (secondary channel above), also known as 3+7, reserves the first 9 out of the 11 channels available.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The specification calls for requiring one primary 20 MHz channel as well as a secondary adjacent channel spaced ±20 MHz away.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The primary channel is used for communications with clients incapable of 40 MHz mode.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] When in 40 MHz mode, the center frequency is actually the mean of the primary and secondary channels.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Local regulations may restrict certain channels from operation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] For example, Channels 12 and 13 are normally unavailable for use as either a primary or secondary channel in North America.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] For further information, see List of WLAN channels.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The Wi-Fi Alliance has upgraded its suite of compatibility tests for some enhancements that were finalized after a 2.0.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Furthermore, it has affirmed that all draft-n certified products remain compatible with the products conforming to the final standards.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The Wi-Fi Alliance began certifying products based on IEEE 802.11n draft 2.0 mid-2007.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] This certification program established a set of features and a level of interoperability across vendors supporting those features, thus providing one definition of "draft n" to ensure compatibility and interoperability.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The baseline certification covers both 20 MHz and 40 MHz wide channels, and up to two spatial streams, for maximum throughputs of 144.4 Mbit/s for 20 MHz and 300 Mbit/s for 40 MHz (with short guard interval).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] A number of vendors in both the consumer and enterprise spaces have built products that have achieved this certification.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The first meeting of the High-Throughput Study Group (HTSG) was held.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Earlier in the year, in the Wireless Next Generation standing committee (WNG SC), presentations were heard on why they need change and what the target throughput would be required to justify the amendments.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Compromise was reached in May 2002 to delay the start of the Study Group until September to allow 11g to complete major work during the July 2002 session.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The IEEE-SA New Standards Committee (NesCom) approved the Project Authorization Request (PAR) for the purpose of amending the 802.11-2007 standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The new 802.11 Task Group (TGn) is to develop a new amendment.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] TGn will be the 5th amendment to the 802.11-2007 standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Mbit/s, as measured at the MAC data service access point (SAP).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The first meeting of the new 802.11 Task Group (TGn).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Proposals were downselected to a single proposal, but there is not a 75% consensus on the one proposal.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Further efforts were expended over the next 3 sessions without being able to agree on one proposal.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Previous competitors TGn Sync, WWiSE, and a third group, MITMOT, said that they would merge their respective proposals as a draft.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The standardization process was expected to be completed by the second quarter of 2009.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The IEEE 802.11n Task Group approved the Joint Proposal's specification, enhanced by EWC's draft specification.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] IEEE 802.11 Working Group sent the 802.11n draft to its first letter ballot, allowing the 500+ 802.11 voters to review the document and suggest bug fixes, changes, and improvements.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The IEEE 802.11 Working Group voted not to forward draft 1.0 of the proposed 802.11n standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] To proceed to the next step in the IEEE standards process, a majority vote of 75% is required.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] This letter ballot also generated approximately 12,000 comments—many more than anticipated.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] TGn voted to accept draft version 1.06, incorporating all accepted technical and editorial comment resolutions prior to this meeting.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] An additional 800 comment resolutions were approved during the November session which will be incorporated into the next revision of the draft.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] As of this meeting, three of the 18 comment topic ad hoc groups chartered in May had completed their work, and 88% of the technical comments had been resolved, with approximately 370 remaining.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The IEEE 802.11 Working Group unanimously (100 yes, 0 no, 5 abstaining) approved a request by the 802.11n Task Group to issue a new draft 2.0 of the proposed standard.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Draft 2.0 was based on the Task Group's working draft version 1.10.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Draft 2.0 was at this point in time the cumulative result of thousands of changes to the 11n document as based on all previous comments.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The results of Letter Ballot 95, a 15-day Procedural vote, passed with 97.99% approval and 2.01% disapproval.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] On the same day, 802.11 Working Group announced the opening of Letter Ballot 97.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] It invited detailed technical comments to closed on 9 March 2007.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Letter Ballot 97, the 30-day Technical vote to approve draft 2.0, closed.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] They were announced by IEEE 802 leadership during the Orlando Plenary on 12 March 2007.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The ballot passed with an 83.4% approval, above the 75% minimum approval threshold.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] There were still approximately 3,076 unique comments, which were to be individually examined for incorporation into the next revision of draft 2.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The Wi-Fi Alliance announced its official certification program for devices based on draft 2.0.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Task Group agreed on all outstanding issues for draft 2.07.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Draft 3.0 is authorized, with the expectation that it go to a sponsor ballot in November 2007.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Draft 3.0 approved (240 voted affirmative, 43 negative, and 27 abstained).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] The editor was authorized to produce draft 3.01.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] This version incorporates previously approved technical and editorial comments.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] There remain 127 unresolved technical comments.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] It was expected that all remaining comments will be resolved and that TGn and WG11 would subsequently release draft 4.0 for working group recirculation ballot following the March meeting.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Draft 5.0 approved and anticipated publication timeline modified.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Draft 7.0 forwarded to sponsor ballot; the sponsor ballot was approved (158 for, 45 against, 21 abstaining); 241 comments were received.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Draft 10.0 passed sponsor ballot recirculation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Draft 11.0 passed sponsor ballot recirculation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Final WG Approval passed with 53 approve, 1 against, 6 abstain.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/802-11n] Unanimous approval to send Final WG draft 11.0 to RevCom.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The earliest experimental AM transmissions began in the early 1900s.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, widespread AM broadcasting was not established until the 1920s, following the development of vacuum tube receivers and transmitters.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] AM radio remained the dominant method of broadcasting for the next 30 years, a period called the "Golden Age of Radio", until television broadcasting became widespread in the 1950s and received much of the programming previously carried by radio.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Later, AM radio's audiences declined greatly due to competition from FM radio, digital radio, satellite radio, Internet radio, music streaming services, and podcasting.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Thus, AM broadcasters tend to specialize in spoken-word formats, such as talk radio, all-news radio and sports radio, with music formats primarily for FM and digital stations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] — Red Barber, *The Broadcasters*, 1970, pp.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In October 1898, a London publication, *The Electrician*, noted that "there are rare cases where, as Dr. [Oliver] Lodge once expressed it, it might be advantageous to 'shout' the message, spreading it broadcast to receivers in all directions".
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, it was recognized that this would involve significant financial issues, as that same year *The Electrician* also commented "did not Prof.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] On January 1, 1902, Nathan Stubblefield gave a short-range "wireless telephone" demonstration, that included simultaneously broadcasting speech and music to seven locations throughout Murray, Kentucky.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The earliest public radiotelegraph broadcasts were provided as government services, beginning with daily time signals inaugurated on January 1, 1905, by a number of U.S.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In Europe, signals transmitted from a station located on the Eiffel Tower were received throughout much of Europe.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In both the United States and France this led to a small market of receiver lines geared for jewelers who needed accurate time to set their clocks, including the Ondophone in France, and the De Forest RS-100 Jewelers Time Receiver in the United States.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The ability to pick up time signal broadcasts, in addition to Morse code weather reports and news summaries, also attracted the interest of amateur radio enthusiasts.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] It was immediately recognized that, much like the telegraph had preceded the invention of the telephone, the ability to make audio radio transmissions would be a significant technical advance.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Despite this knowledge, it still took two decades to perfect the technology needed to make quality audio transmissions.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In addition, the telephone had rarely been used for distributing entertainment, outside of a few "telephone newspaper" systems, most of which were established in Europe, beginning with the Paris Théâtrophone.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] With this in mind, most early radiotelephone development envisioned that the device would be more profitably developed as a "wireless telephone" for personal communication, or for providing links where regular telephone lines could not be run, rather than for the uncertain finances of broadcasting.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The person generally credited as the primary early developer of AM technology is Canadian-born inventor Reginald Fessenden.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The original spark-gap radio transmitters were impractical for transmitting audio, since they produced discontinuous pulses known as "damped waves".
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Fessenden realized that what was needed was a new type of radio transmitter that produced steady "undamped" (better known as "continuous wave") signals, which could then be "modulated" to reflect the sounds being transmitted.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Fessenden's basic approach was disclosed in U.S.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Patent 706,737, which he applied for on May 29, 1901, and was issued the next year.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] It called for the use of a high-speed alternator (referred to as "an alternating-current dynamo") that generated "pure sine waves" and produced "a continuous train of radiant waves of substantially uniform strength", or, in modern terminology, a continuous-wave (CW) transmitter.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Fessenden began his research on audio transmissions while doing developmental work for the United States Weather Service on Cobb Island, Maryland.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Because he did not yet have a continuous-wave transmitter, initially he worked with an experimental "high-frequency spark" transmitter, taking advantage of the fact that the higher the spark rate, the closer a spark-gap transmission comes to producing continuous waves.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] He later reported that, in the fall of 1900, he successfully transmitted speech over a distance of about 1.6 kilometers (one mile), which appears to have been the first successful audio transmission using radio signals.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, at this time the sound was far too distorted to be commercially practical.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] For a time he continued working with more sophisticated high-frequency spark transmitters, including versions that used compressed air, which began to take on some of the characteristics of arc-transmitters.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Fessenden attempted to sell this form of radiotelephone for point-to-point communication, but was unsuccessful.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Fessenden's work with high-frequency spark transmissions was only a temporary measure.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The next step, adopted from standard wire-telephone practice, was to insert a simple carbon microphone into the transmission line, to modulate the carrier wave signal to produce AM audio transmissions.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, it would take many years of expensive development before even a prototype alternator-transmitter would be ready, and a few years beyond that for high-power versions to become available.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Fessenden worked with General Electric's (GE) Ernst F.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Alexanderson, who in August 1906, delivered an improved model which operated at a transmitting frequency of approximately 50 kHz, although at low power.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The alternator-transmitter achieved the goal of transmitting quality audio signals, but the lack of any way to amplify the signals meant they were somewhat weak.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] On December 21, 1906, Fessenden made an extensive demonstration of the new alternator-transmitter at Brant Rock, Massachusetts, showing its utility for point-to-point wireless telephony, including interconnecting his stations to the wire telephone network.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] As part of the demonstration, speech was transmitted 18 kilometers (11 miles) to a listening site at Plymouth, Massachusetts.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Because there was no way to amplify electrical currents at this time, modulation was usually accomplished by a carbon microphone inserted directly in the antenna wire.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] This meant that the full transmitter power flowed through the microphone, and even using water cooling, the power handling ability of the microphones severely limited the power of the transmissions.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Ultimately only a small number of large and powerful Alexanderson alternators would be developed.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, they would be almost exclusively used for long-range radiotelegraph communication, and occasionally for radiotelephone experimentation, but were never used for general broadcasting.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Almost all of the continuous wave AM transmissions made prior to 1915 were made by versions of the arc converter transmitter, which had been initially developed by Valdemar Poulsen in 1903.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Arc transmitters worked by producing a pulsating electrical arc in an enclosed hydrogen atmosphere.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] They were much more compact than alternator transmitters, and could operate on somewhat higher transmitting frequencies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, they suffered from some of the same deficiencies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The lack of any means to amplify electrical currents meant that, like the alternator transmitters, modulation was usually accomplished by a microphone inserted directly in the antenna wire, which again resulted in overheating issues, even with the use of water-cooled microphones.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Thus, transmitter powers tended to be limited.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The arc was also somewhat unstable, which reduced audio quality.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Experimenters who used arc transmitters for their radiotelephone research included Ernst Ruhmer, Quirino Majorana, Charles "Doc" Herrold, and Lee de Forest.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Advances in vacuum tube technology (called "valves" in British usage), especially after around 1915, revolutionized radio technology.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Vacuum tube devices could be used to amplify electrical currents, which overcame the overheating issues of needing to insert microphones directly in the transmission antenna circuit.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Vacuum tube transmitters also provided high-quality AM signals, and could operate on higher transmitting frequencies than alternator and arc transmitters.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Vacuum tubes remained the central technology of radio for 40 years, until transistors began to dominate in the late 1950s, and are still used in the highest power broadcast transmitters.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Unlike telegraph and telephone systems, which used completely different types of equipment, most radio receivers were equally suitable for both radiotelegraph and radiotelephone reception.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 1903 and 1904, the electrolytic detector and thermionic diode (Fleming valve) were invented by Reginald Fessenden and John Ambrose Fleming, respectively.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Most important, in 1904–1906, the crystal detector, the simplest and cheapest AM detector, was developed by G.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Homemade crystal radios spread rapidly during the next 15 years, providing ready audiences for the first radio broadcasts.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] One limitation of crystals sets was the lack of amplifying the signals, so listeners had to use earphones, and it required the development of vacuum-tube receivers before loudspeakers could be used.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The dynamic cone loudspeaker, invented in 1924, greatly improved audio frequency response over the previous horn speakers, allowing music to be reproduced with good fidelity.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] AM radio offered the highest sound quality available in a home audio device prior to the introduction of the high-fidelity, long-playing record in the late 1940s.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Listening habits changed in the 1960s due to the introduction of the revolutionary transistor radio (Regency TR-1, the first transistor radio released December 1954), which was made possible by the invention of the transistor in 1948.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] (The transistor was invented at Bell labs and released in June 1948.) Their compact size — small enough to fit in a shirt pocket — and lower power requirements, compared to vacuum tubes, meant that for the first time radio receivers were readily portable.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The transistor radio became the most widely used communication device in history, with billions manufactured by the 1970s.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Radio became a ubiquitous "companion medium" which people could take with them anywhere they went.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The demarcation between what is considered "experimental" and "organized" broadcasting is largely arbitrary.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Following World War I, the number of stations providing a regular broadcasting service greatly increased, primarily due to advances in vacuum-tube technology.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, there were numerous cases of entertainment broadcasts being presented on a regular schedule before their formal recognition by government regulators.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Because most longwave radio frequencies were used for international radiotelegraph communication, a majority of early broadcasting stations operated on mediumwave frequencies, whose limited range generally restricted them to local audiences.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] One method for overcoming this limitation, as well as a method for sharing program costs, was to create radio networks, linking stations together with telephone lines to provide a nationwide audience.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In the U.S., the American Telephone and Telegraph Company (AT&T) was the first organization to create a radio network, and also to promote commercial advertising, which it called "toll" broadcasting.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Its flagship station, WEAF (now WFAN) in New York City, sold blocks of airtime to commercial sponsors that developed entertainment shows containing commercial messages.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] AT&T held a monopoly on quality telephone lines, and by 1924 had linked 12 stations in Eastern cities into a "chain".
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The Radio Corporation of America (RCA), General Electric, and Westinghouse organized a competing network around its own flagship station, RCA's WJZ (now WABC) in New York City, but were hampered by AT&T's refusal to lease connecting lines or allow them to sell airtime.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 1926, AT&T sold its radio operations to RCA, which used them to form the nucleus of the new NBC network.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] By the 1930s, most of the major radio stations in the country were affiliated with networks owned by two companies, NBC and CBS.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 1934, a third national network, the Mutual Radio Network, was formed as a cooperative owned by its stations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] A second country which quickly adopted network programming was the United Kingdom, and its national network quickly became a prototype for a state-managed monopoly of broadcasting.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] A rising interest in radio broadcasting by the British public pressured the government to reintroduce the service, following its suspension in 1920.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, the government also wanted to avoid what it termed the "chaotic" U.S. experience of allowing large numbers of stations to operate with few restrictions.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] There were also concerns about broadcasting becoming dominated by the Marconi company.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Arrangements were made for six large radio manufacturers to form a consortium, the British Broadcasting Company (BBC), established on October 18, 1922, which was given a monopoly on broadcasting.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] This enterprise was supported by a tax on radio sets sales, plus an annual license fee on receivers, collected by the Post Office.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Initially the eight stations were allowed regional autonomy.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 1927, the original broadcasting organization was replaced by a government chartered British Broadcasting Corporation. an independent nonprofit supported solely by a 10 shilling receiver license fee.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Both highbrow and mass-appeal programs were carried by the National and Regional networks.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The period from the early 1920s through the 1940s is often called the "Golden Age of Radio".
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] During this period AM radio was the main source of home entertainment, until it was replaced by television.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] For the first time entertainment was provided from outside the home, replacing traditional forms of entertainment such as oral storytelling and music from family members.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] New forms were created, including radio plays, mystery serials, soap operas, quiz shows, variety hours, situation comedies and children's shows.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Radio news, including remote reporting, allowed listeners to be vicariously present at notable events.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Radio greatly eased the isolation of rural life.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Political officials could now speak directly to millions of citizens.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] One of the first to take advantage of this was American president Franklin Roosevelt, who became famous for his fireside chats during the Great Depression.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, broadcasting also provided the means to use propaganda as a powerful government tool, and contributed to the rise of fascist and communist ideologies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In the 1940s, two new broadcast media, FM radio and television, began to provide extensive competition with the established broadcasting services.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The AM radio industry suffered a serious loss of audience and advertising revenue, and coped by developing new strategies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Instead of live music, most stations began playing less expensive recorded music.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In the late 1960s and 1970s, top 40 rock and roll stations in the U.S. and Canada such as WABC and CHUM transmitted highly processed and extended audio to 11 kHz, successfully attracting huge audiences.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In the late 1970s, spurred by the exodus of musical programming to FM stations, the AM radio industry in the United States developed technology for broadcasting in stereo.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Other nations adopted AM stereo, most commonly choosing Motorola's C-QUAM, and in 1993, the United States also made the C-QUAM system its standard, after a period allowing four different standards to compete.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The selection of a single standard improved acceptance of AM stereo, however overall there was limited adoption of AM stereo worldwide, and interest declined after 1990.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] With the continued migration of AM stations away from music to news, sports, and talk formats, receiver manufacturers saw little reason to adopt the more expensive stereo tuners, and thus radio stations have little incentive to upgrade to stereo transmission.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] This sometimes results in the sale of the transmitter site, with the station relocating to a more distant shared site using significantly less power, or completely shutting down operations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The ongoing development of alternative transmission systems, including DAB, satellite radio, and HD radio, continued the decline of the popularity of the traditional broadcast technologies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] These new options, including the introduction of Internet streaming, particularly resulted in the reduction of shortwave transmissions, as international broadcasters found ways to reach their audiences more easily.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However the United States Congress has introduced a bill to require all vehicles sold in the US to have an AM receiver to receive emergency broadcasts.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The FM broadcast band was established in 1941 in the United States, and at the time some suggested that the AM band would soon be eliminated.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 1948, wide-band FM's inventor, Edwin H.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Since then the AM band's share of the audience has continued to decline.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 1987, the elimination of the Fairness Doctrine requirement meant that talk shows, which were commonly carried by AM stations, could adopt a more focused presentation on controversial topics, without the distraction of having to provide airtime for any contrasting opinions.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In addition, satellite distribution made it possible for programs to be economically carried on a national scale.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The introduction of nationwide talk shows, most prominently Rush Limbaugh's beginning in 1988, was sometimes credited with "saving" AM radio.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, these stations tended to attract older listeners who were of lesser interest to advertisers, and AM radio's audience share continued to erode.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 1961, the FCC adopted a single standard for FM stereo transmissions, which was widely credited with enhancing FM's popularity.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Developing the technology for AM broadcasting in stereo was challenging due to the need to limit the transmissions to a 20 kHz bandwidth, while also making the transmissions backward compatible with existing non-stereo receivers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 1990, the FCC authorized an AM stereo standard developed by Magnavox, but two years later revised its decision to instead approve four competing implementations, saying it would "let the marketplace decide" which was best.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The lack of a common standard resulted in consumer confusion and increased the complexity and cost of producing AM stereo receivers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 1993, the FCC again revised its policy, by selecting C-QUAM as the sole AM stereo implementation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] On June 8, 1988, an International Telecommunication Union (ITU)-sponsored conference held at Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, adopted provisions, effective July 1, 1990, to extend the upper end of the Region 2 AM broadcast band, by adding ten frequencies which spanned from 1610 kHz to 1700 kHz.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] At this time it was suggested that as many as 500 U.S. stations could be assigned to the new frequencies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] On April 12, 1990, the FCC voted to begin the process of populating the expanded band, with the main priority being the reduction of interference on the existing AM band, by transferring selected stations to the new frequencies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] It was now estimated that the expanded band could accommodate around 300 U.S. stations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, it turned out that the number of possible station reassignments was much lower, with a 2006 accounting reporting that, out of 4,758 licensed U.S.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] AM stations, only 56 were now operating on the expanded band.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] HD Radio is a digital audio broadcasting method developed by iBiquity.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 2007, nighttime operation was also authorized.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The number of hybrid mode AM stations is not exactly known, because the FCC does not keep track of the stations employing the system, and some authorized stations have later turned it off.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] But as of 2020, the commission estimated that fewer than 250 AM stations were transmitting hybrid mode signals.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Despite the various actions, AM band audiences continued to contract, and the number of stations began to slowly decline.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] A 2009 FCC review reported that "The story of AM radio over the last 50 years has been a transition from being the dominant form of audio entertainment for all age groups to being almost non-existent to the youngest demographic groups.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Among persons aged 12–24, AM accounts for only 4% of listening, while FM accounts for 96%.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Among persons aged 25–34, AM accounts for only 9% of listening, while FM accounts for 91%.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 2009, the FCC made a major regulatory change, when it adopted a policy allowing AM stations to simulcast over FM translator stations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Translators had previously been available only to FM broadcasters, in order to increase coverage in fringe areas.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Their assignment for use by AM stations was intended to approximate the station's daytime coverage, which in cases where the stations reduced power at night, often resulted in expanded nighttime coverage.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Although the translator stations are not permitted to originate programming when the "primary" AM station is broadcasting, they are permitted to do so during nighttime hours for AM stations licensed for daytime-only operation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Prior to the adoption of the new policy, as of March 18, 2009, the FCC had issued 215 Special Temporary Authority grants for FM translators relaying AM stations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] After creation of the new policy, by 2011, there were approximately 500 in operation, and as of 2020, approximately 2,800 of the 4,570 licensed AM stations were rebroadcasting on one or more FM translators.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 2009, the FCC stated that "We do not intend to allow these cross-service translators to be used as surrogates for FM stations".
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, based on station slogans, especially in the case of recently adopted musical formats, in most cases the expectation is that listeners will primarily be tuning into the FM signal rather than the nominally "primary" AM station.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] A 2020 review noted that "for many owners, keeping their AM stations on the air now is pretty much just about retaining their FM translator footprint rather than keeping the AM on the air on its own merits".
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In 2018, the FCC, led by then-Commission Chairman Ajit Pai, proposed greatly reducing signal protection for 50 kW Class A "clear channel" stations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] This would allow co-channel secondary stations to operate with higher powers, especially at night.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] However, the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) expressed concerns that this would reduce the effectiveness of emergency communications.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] In May 2023, a bipartisan group of lawmakers in the United States introduced legislation making it illegal for automakers to eliminate AM radio from their cars.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The lawmakers argue that AM radio is an important tool for public safety due to being a component of the Emergency Alert System (EAS).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] Some automakers have been eliminating AM radio from their electric vehicles (EVs) due to interference from the electric motors, but the lawmakers argue that this is a safety risk and that car owners should have access to AM radio regardless of the type of vehicle they drive.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] The proposed legislation would require all new vehicles to include AM radio at no additional charge, and it would also require automakers that have already eliminated AM radio to inform customers of alternatives.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p01] DRM30 is another standard to broadcast on the AM bands, with implementation in India and China, among other countries.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] AM radio technology is simpler than later transmission systems.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] An AM receiver detects amplitude variations in the radio waves at a particular frequency, then amplifies changes in the signal voltage to operate a loudspeaker or earphone.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] In large urban centers, AM radio signals can be severely disrupted by metal structures and tall buildings.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] As a result, AM radio tends to do best in areas where FM frequencies are in short supply, or in thinly populated or mountainous areas where FM coverage is poor.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] Great care must be taken to avoid mutual interference between stations operating on the same frequency.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] In general, an AM transmission needs to be about 20 times stronger than an interfering signal to avoid a reduction in quality, in contrast to FM signals, where the "capture effect" means that the dominant signal needs to only be about twice as strong as the interfering one.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] To allow room for more stations on the mediumwave broadcast band in the United States, in June 1989, the FCC adopted a National Radio Systems Committee (NRSC) standard that limited maximum transmitted audio bandwidth to 10.2 kHz, limiting occupied bandwidth to 20.4 kHz.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] The former audio limitation was 15 kHz resulting in bandwidth of 30 kHz.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] Another common limitation on AM fidelity is the result of receiver design, although some efforts have been made to improve this, notably through the AMAX standards adopted in the United States.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] AM broadcasts are used on several frequency bands.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] The allocation of these bands is governed by the ITU's Radio Regulations and, on the national level, by each country's telecommunications administration (the FCC in the U.S., for example) subject to international agreements.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] The frequency ranges given here are those that are allocated to stations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] Because of the bandwidth taken up by the sidebands, the range allocated for the band as a whole is usually about 5 kHz wider on either side.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] Most of the earliest broadcasting experiments took place on longwave frequencies; however, complaints about interference from existing services, particularly the military, led to most broadcasting moving to higher frequencies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] Most broadcast services use AM transmissions, although some use a modified version of AM such as Single-sideband modulation (SSB) or an AM-compatible version of SSB such as "SSB with carrier reinserted".
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] Beginning in the mid-1930s, the United States evaluated options for the establishment of broadcasting stations using much higher transmitting frequencies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] In October 1937, the FCC announced a second band of AM stations, consisting of 75 channels spanning from 41.02 to 43.98 MHz, which were informally called *Apex*.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] The 40 kHz spacing between adjacent frequencies was four times that of the 10 kHz spacing used on the standard AM broadcast band, which reduced adjacent-frequency interference, and provided more bandwidth for high-fidelity programming.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] However, this band was eliminated effective on January 1, 1941, after the FCC determined that establishing a band of FM stations was preferable.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] Beginning in the mid-1930s, starting with "The Brown Network" at Brown University in Providence, Rhode Island, a very low power broadcasting method known as carrier current was developed, and mostly adopted on U.S. college campuses.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] In this approach AM broadcast signals are distributed over electric power lines, which radiate a signal receivable at a short distance from the lines.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] In Switzerland a system known as "wire broadcasting" (*Telefonrundspruch* in German) transmitted AM signals over telephone lines in the longwave band until 1998, when it was shut down.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] In the UK, Rediffusion was an early pioneer of AM radio cable distribution.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] Hybrid digital broadcast systems, which combine (mono analog) AM transmission with digital sidebands, have started to be used around the world.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] In the United States, iBiquity's proprietary HD Radio has been adopted and approved by the FCC for medium wave transmissions, while Digital Radio Mondiale is a more open effort often used on the shortwave bands, and can be used alongside many AM broadcasts.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] Both of these standards are capable of broadcasting audio of significantly greater fidelity than that of standard AM with current bandwidth limitations, and a theoretical frequency response of 0–16 kHz, in addition to stereo sound and text data.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] Some microbroadcasters, especially those in the United States operating under the FCC's Part 15 rules, and pirate radio operators on mediumwave and shortwave, achieve greater range than possible on the FM band.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] On mediumwave these stations often transmit on 1610 kHz to 1710 kHz.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/am-radio-p02] Microbroadcasting and pirate radio have generally been supplanted by streaming audio on the Internet, but some schools and hobbyists still use LPAM transmissions.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] The **ampere** (/ˈæmpɛər/ ⓘ *AM-pair*, US: /ˈæmpɪər/ ⓘ *AM-peer*; symbol: **A**), often shortened to **amp**, is the unit of electric current in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] One ampere is equal to 1 coulomb (C) moving past a point per second.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] It is named after French mathematician and physicist André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836), considered the father of electromagnetism along with Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] Prior to the redefinition, the ampere was defined as the current passing through two parallel wires 1 metre apart that produces a magnetic force of 2×10−7 newtons per metre.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] The earlier CGS system has two units of current, one structured similarly to the SI's and the other using Coulomb's law as a fundamental relationship, with the CGS unit of charge defined by measuring the force between two charged metal plates.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] The CGS unit of current is then defined as one unit of charge per second.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] The ampere is named for French physicist and mathematician André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836), who studied electromagnetism and laid the foundation of electrodynamics.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] In recognition of Ampère's contributions to the creation of modern electrical science, an international convention, signed at the 1881 International Exposition of Electricity, established the ampere as a standard unit of electrical measurement for electric current.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] The ampere was originally defined as one tenth of the unit of electric current in the centimetre–gram–second system of units.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] That unit, now known as the abampere, was defined as the amount of current that generates a force of two dynes per centimetre of length between two wires one centimetre apart.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] The size of the unit was chosen so that the units derived from it in the MKSA system would be conveniently sized.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] The "international ampere" was an early realisation of the ampere, defined as the current that would deposit 0.001118 grams of silver per second from a silver nitrate solution.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] Later, more accurate measurements revealed that this current is 0.99985 A.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] Since power is defined as the product of current and voltage, the ampere can alternatively be expressed in terms of the other units using the relationship *I* = *P*/*V*, and thus 1 A = 1 W/V.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] Current can be measured by a multimeter, a device that can measure electrical voltage, current, and resistance.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] Ampère's force law states that there is an attractive or repulsive force between two parallel wires carrying an electric current.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] This force was used in the formal definition of the ampere, giving the vacuum magnetic permeability (magnetic constant, *μ*0) a value of exactly 4π × 10−7 henries per metre (H/m, equivalent to N/A2).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] The SI unit of charge, the coulomb, was then defined as "the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere".
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] In general, charge Q was determined by steady current I flowing for a time t as *Q* = *It*.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] Techniques to establish the realisation of an ampere had a relative uncertainty of approximately a few parts in 107, and involved realisations of the watt, the ohm and the volt.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] The SI unit of charge, the coulomb, "is the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere".
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] The relation of the ampere (A = C/s) to the coulomb (C) is the same as that of the watt (W = J/s) to the joule (J).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] These SI derived units can either be given special names e.g. watt, volt, lux, etc. or defined in terms of others, e.g. metre per second.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] There are also some SI units that are frequently used in the context of electrical engineering and electrical appliances, but are defined independently of the ampere, notably the hertz, joule, watt, candela, lumen, and lux.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/ampere] Like other SI units, the ampere can be modified by adding a prefix that multiplies it by a power of 10.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] An **amplifier**, **electronic amplifier** or (informally) **amp** is an electronic device that can increase the magnitude of a signal (a time-varying voltage or current).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] It is a two-port electronic circuit that uses electric power from a power supply to increase the amplitude (magnitude of the voltage or current) of a signal applied to its input terminals, producing a proportionally greater amplitude signal at its output.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The amount of amplification provided by an amplifier is measured by its gain: the ratio of output voltage, current, or power to input.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] An amplifier is defined as a circuit that has a power gain greater than one.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] An amplifier can be either a separate piece of equipment or an electrical circuit contained within another device.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Amplification is fundamental to modern electronics, and amplifiers are widely used in almost all electronic equipment.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Amplifiers can be categorized in different ways.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] One is by the frequency of the electronic signal being amplified.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] For example, audio amplifiers amplify signals of less than 20 kHz, radio frequency (RF) amplifiers amplify frequencies in the range between 20 kHz and 300 GHz, and servo amplifiers and instrumentation amplifiers may work with very low frequencies down to direct current.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Amplifiers can also be categorized by their physical placement in the signal chain; a preamplifier may precede other signal processing stages, for example, while a power amplifier is usually used after other amplifier stages to provide enough output power for the final use of the signal.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The first practical electrical device which could amplify was the triode vacuum tube, invented in 1906 by Lee de Forest, which led to the first amplifiers around 1912.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The first practical prominent device that could amplify was the triode vacuum tube, invented in 1906 by Lee De Forest, which led to the first amplifiers around 1912.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Vacuum tubes were used in almost all amplifiers until the 1960s–1970s when transistors replaced them.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Today, most amplifiers use transistors, but vacuum tubes continue to be used in some applications.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The development of audio communication technology in form of the telephone, first patented in 1876, created the need to increase the amplitude of electrical signals to extend the transmission of signals over increasingly long distances.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In telegraphy, this problem had been solved with intermediate devices at stations that replenished the dissipated energy by operating a signal recorder and transmitter back-to-back, forming a relay, so that a local energy source at each intermediate station powered the next leg of transmission.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] For duplex transmission, i.e. sending and receiving in both directions, bi-directional relay repeaters were developed starting with the work of C.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Duplex transmission was essential for telephony and the problem was not satisfactorily solved until 1904, when H.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Shreeve of the American Telephone and Telegraph Company improved existing attempts at constructing a telephone repeater consisting of back-to-back carbon-granule transmitter and electrodynamic receiver pairs.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The Shreeve repeater was first tested on a line between Boston and Amesbury, MA, and more refined devices remained in service for some time.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] After the turn of the century it was found that negative resistance mercury lamps could amplify, and were also tried in repeaters, with little success.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The development of thermionic valves which began around 1902, provided an entirely electronic method of amplifying signals.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The first practical version of such devices was the Audion triode, invented in 1906 by Lee De Forest, which led to the first amplifiers around 1912.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Since the only previous device which was widely used to strengthen a signal was the relay used in telegraph systems, the amplifying vacuum tube was first called an *electron relay*.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The terms *amplifier* and *amplification*, derived from the Latin *amplificare*, (*to enlarge or expand*), were first used for this new capability around 1915 when triodes became widespread.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The amplifying vacuum tube revolutionized electrical technology.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] It made possible long-distance telephone lines, public address systems, radio broadcasting, talking motion pictures, practical audio recording, radar, television, and the first computers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] For 50 years virtually all consumer electronic devices used vacuum tubes.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Early tube amplifiers often had positive feedback (regeneration), which could increase gain but also make the amplifier unstable and prone to oscillation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Much of the mathematical theory of amplifiers was developed at Bell Telephone Laboratories during the 1920s to 1940s.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Distortion levels in early amplifiers were high, usually around 5%, until 1934, when Harold Black developed negative feedback; this allowed the distortion levels to be greatly reduced, at the cost of lower gain.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Other advances in the theory of amplification were made by Harry Nyquist and Hendrik Wade Bode.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The vacuum tube was virtually the only amplifying device, other than specialized power devices such as the magnetic amplifier and amplidyne, for 40 years.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Power control circuitry used magnetic amplifiers until the latter half of the twentieth century when power semiconductor devices became more economical, with higher operating speeds.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The old Shreeve electroacoustic carbon repeaters were used in adjustable amplifiers in telephone subscriber sets for the hearing impaired until the transistor provided smaller and higher quality amplifiers in the 1950s.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The first working transistor was a point-contact transistor invented by John Bardeen and Walter Brattain in 1947 at Bell Labs, where William Shockley later invented the bipolar junction transistor (BJT) in 1948.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] They were followed by the invention of the metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET) by Mohamed M.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Atalla and Dawon Kahng at Bell Labs in 1959.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Due to MOSFET scaling, the ability to scale down to increasingly small sizes, the MOSFET has since become the most widely used amplifier.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The replacement of electron tubes with transistors during the 1960s and 1970s created a revolution in electronics, making possible a large class of portable electronic devices, such as the transistor radio developed in 1954.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Today, use of vacuum tubes is limited to some high power applications, such as radio transmitters, as well as some musical instrument and high-end audiophile amplifiers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Beginning in the 1970s, more and more transistors were connected on a single chip thereby creating higher scales of integration (such as small-scale, medium-scale and large-scale integration) in integrated circuits.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Many amplifiers commercially available today are based on integrated circuits.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] For special purposes, other active elements have been used.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] For example, in the early days of the satellite communication, parametric amplifiers were used.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The core circuit was a diode whose capacitance was changed by an RF signal created locally.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Under certain conditions, this RF signal provided energy that was modulated by the extremely weak satellite signal received at the earth station.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Advances in digital electronics since the late 20th century provided new alternatives to the conventional linear-gain amplifiers by using digital switching to vary the pulse-shape of fixed amplitude signals, resulting in devices such as the Class-D amplifier.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In principle, an amplifier is an electrical two-port network that produces a signal at the output port that is a replica of the signal applied to the input port, but increased in magnitude.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The input port can be idealized as either being a voltage input, which takes no current, with the output proportional to the voltage across the port; or a current input, with no voltage across it, in which the output is proportional to the current through the port.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The output port can be idealized as being either a dependent voltage source, with zero source resistance and its output voltage dependent on the input; or a dependent current source, with infinite source resistance and the output current dependent on the input.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Combinations of these choices lead to four types of ideal amplifiers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In real amplifiers the ideal impedances are not possible to achieve, but these ideal elements can be used to construct equivalent circuits of real amplifiers by adding impedances (resistance, capacitance and inductance) to the input and output.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] For any particular circuit, a small-signal analysis is often used to find the actual impedance.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] A small-signal AC test current *Ix* is applied to the input or output node, all external sources are set to AC zero, and the corresponding alternating voltage *Vx* across the test current source determines the impedance seen at that node as *R = Vx / Ix*.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Amplifiers designed to attach to a transmission line at input and output, especially RF amplifiers, do not fit into this classification approach.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Rather than dealing with voltage or current individually, they ideally couple with an input or output impedance matched to the transmission line impedance, that is, match *ratios* of voltage to current.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Many real RF amplifiers come close to this ideal.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Although, for a given appropriate source and load impedance, RF amplifiers can be characterized as amplifying voltage or current, they fundamentally are amplifying power.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Amplifiers are described according to the properties of their inputs, their outputs, and how they relate.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] All amplifiers have gain, a multiplication factor that relates the magnitude of some property of the output signal to a property of the input signal.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The gain may be specified as the ratio of output voltage to input voltage (voltage gain), output power to input power (power gain), or some combination of current, voltage, and power.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In many cases the property of the output that varies is dependent on the same property of the input, making the gain unitless (though often expressed in decibels (dB)).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Most amplifiers are designed to be linear.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] That is, they provide constant gain for any normal input level and output signal.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] If an amplifier's gain is not linear, the output signal can become distorted.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] There are, however, cases where variable gain is useful.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Certain signal processing applications use exponential gain amplifiers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Amplifiers are usually designed to function well in a specific application, for example: radio and television transmitters and receivers, high-fidelity ("hi-fi") stereo equipment, microcomputers and other digital equipment, and guitar and other instrument amplifiers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Every amplifier includes at least one active device, such as a vacuum tube or transistor.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Negative feedback is a technique used in most modern amplifiers to increase bandwidth, reduce distortion, and control gain.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In a negative feedback amplifier part of the output is fed back and added to the input in the opposite phase, subtracting from the input.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The main effect is to reduce the overall gain of the system.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] However, any unwanted signals introduced by the amplifier, such as distortion are also fed back.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Since they are not part of the original input, they are added to the input in opposite phase, subtracting them from the input.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In this way, negative feedback also reduces nonlinearity, distortion and other errors introduced by the amplifier.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Large amounts of negative feedback can reduce errors to the point that the response of the amplifier itself becomes almost irrelevant as long as it has a large gain, and the output performance of the system (the "closed loop performance") is defined entirely by the components in the feedback loop.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] This technique is used particularly with operational amplifiers (op-amps).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Non-feedback amplifiers can achieve only about 1% distortion for audio-frequency signals.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] With negative feedback, distortion can typically be reduced to 0.001%.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Noise, even crossover distortion, can be practically eliminated.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Negative feedback also compensates for changing temperatures, and degrading or nonlinear components in the gain stage, but any change or nonlinearity in the components in the feedback loop will affect the output.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Indeed, the ability of the feedback loop to define the output is used to make active filter circuits.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Another advantage of negative feedback is that it extends the bandwidth of the amplifier.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The concept of feedback is used in operational amplifiers to precisely define gain, bandwidth, and other parameters entirely based on the components in the feedback loop.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Negative feedback can be applied at each stage of an amplifier to stabilize the operating point of active devices against minor changes in power-supply voltage or device characteristics.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Some feedback, positive or negative, is unavoidable and often undesirable—introduced, for example, by parasitic elements, such as inherent capacitance between input and output of devices such as transistors, and capacitive coupling of external wiring.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Excessive frequency-dependent positive feedback can produce parasitic oscillation and turn an amplifier into an oscillator.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] All amplifiers include some form of active device: this is the device that does the actual amplification.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The active device can be a vacuum tube, discrete solid state component, such as a single transistor, or part of an integrated circuit, as in an op-amp.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Transistor amplifiers (or solid state amplifiers) are the most common type of amplifier in use today.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] A transistor is used as the active element.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The gain of the amplifier is determined by the properties of the transistor itself as well as the circuit it is contained within.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Common active devices in transistor amplifiers include bipolar junction transistors (BJTs) and metal oxide semiconductor field-effect transistors (MOSFETs).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Some common examples are audio amplifiers in a home stereo or public address system, RF high power generation for semiconductor equipment, to RF and microwave applications such as radio transmitters.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Transistor-based amplification can be realized using various configurations: for example a bipolar junction transistor can realize common base, common collector or common emitter amplification; a MOSFET can realize common gate, common source or common drain amplification.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Each configuration has different characteristics.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Vacuum-tube amplifiers (also known as tube amplifiers or valve amplifiers) use a vacuum tube as the active device.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] While semiconductor amplifiers have largely displaced valve amplifiers for low-power applications, valve amplifiers can be much more cost effective in high power applications such as radar, countermeasures equipment, and communications equipment.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Many microwave amplifiers are specially designed valve amplifiers, such as the klystron, gyrotron, traveling wave tube, and crossed-field amplifier, and these microwave valves provide much greater single-device power output at microwave frequencies than solid-state devices.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Vacuum tubes remain in use in some high end audio equipment, as well as in musical instrument amplifiers, due to a preference for "tube sound".
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Magnetic amplifiers are devices somewhat similar to a transformer where one winding is used to control the saturation of a magnetic core and hence alter the impedance of the other winding.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] They have largely fallen out of use due to development in semiconductor amplifiers but are still useful in HVDC control, and in nuclear power control circuitry due to not being affected by radioactivity.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Negative resistances can be used as amplifiers, such as the tunnel diode amplifier.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] A power amplifier is an amplifier designed primarily to increase the power available to a load.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In practice, amplifier power gain depends on the source and load impedances, as well as the inherent voltage and current gain.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] A radio frequency (RF) amplifier design typically optimizes impedances for power transfer, while audio and instrumentation amplifier designs normally optimize input and output impedance for least loading and highest signal integrity.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In general, the power amplifier is the last 'amplifier' or actual circuit in a signal chain (the output stage) and is the amplifier stage that requires attention to power efficiency.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Audio power amplifiers are typically used to drive loudspeakers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] They will often have two output channels and deliver equal power to each.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] An RF power amplifier is found in radio transmitter final stages.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] A servo motor controller amplifies a control voltage to adjust the speed of a motor, or the position of a motorized system.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Power amplifier circuits (output stages) are classified as A, B, AB and C for analog designs—and class D and E for switching designs.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The power amplifier classes are based on the proportion of each input cycle (conduction angle) during which an amplifying device passes current.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The image of the conduction angle derives from amplifying a sinusoidal signal.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] If the device is always on, the conducting angle is 360°.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] If it is on for only half of each cycle, the angle is 180°.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The angle of flow is closely related to the amplifier power efficiency.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] An operational amplifier is an amplifier circuit which typically has very high open loop gain and differential inputs.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Op amps have become very widely used as standardized "gain blocks" in circuits due to their versatility; their gain, bandwidth and other characteristics can be controlled by feedback through an external circuit.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Though the term today commonly applies to integrated circuits, the original operational amplifier design used valves, and later designs used discrete transistor circuits.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] A fully differential amplifier is similar to the operational amplifier, but also has differential outputs.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] These are usually constructed using BJTs or FETs.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] These use balanced transmission lines to separate individual single stage amplifiers, the outputs of which are summed by the same transmission line.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The transmission line is a balanced type with the input at one end and on one side only of the balanced transmission line and the output at the opposite end is also the opposite side of the balanced transmission line.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The gain of each stage adds linearly to the output rather than multiplies one on the other as in a cascade configuration.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] This allows a higher bandwidth to be achieved than could otherwise be realised even with the same gain stage elements.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] These nonlinear amplifiers have much higher efficiencies than linear amps, and are used where the power saving justifies the extra complexity.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Class-D amplifiers are the main example of this type of amplification.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] A negative resistance amplifier is a type of regenerative amplifier that can use the feedback between the transistor's source and gate to transform a capacitive impedance on the transistor's source to a negative resistance on its gate.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Compared to other types of amplifiers, a negative resistance amplifier will require only a tiny amount of power to achieve very high gain, maintaining a good noise figure at the same time.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Video amplifiers are designed to process video signals and have varying bandwidths depending on whether the video signal is for SDTV, EDTV, HDTV 720p or 1080i/p etc.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The specification of the bandwidth itself depends on what kind of filter is used—and at which point (−1 dB or −3 dB for example) the bandwidth is measured.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Certain requirements for step response and overshoot are necessary for an acceptable TV image.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Traveling wave tube amplifiers (TWTAs) are used for high power amplification at low microwave frequencies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] They typically can amplify across a broad spectrum of frequencies; however, they are usually not as tunable as klystrons.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Klystrons are specialized linear-beam vacuum-devices, designed to provide high power, widely tunable amplification of millimetre and sub-millimetre waves.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Klystrons are designed for large scale operations and despite having a narrower bandwidth than TWTAs, they have the advantage of coherently amplifying a reference signal so its output may be precisely controlled in amplitude, frequency and phase.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] New materials like gallium nitride (GaN) or GaN on silicon or on silicon carbide/SiC are emerging in HEMT transistors and applications where improved efficiency, wide bandwidth, operation roughly from few to few tens of GHz with output power of few watts to few hundred of watts are needed.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Depending on the amplifier specifications and size requirements microwave amplifiers can be realised as monolithically integrated, integrated as modules or based on discrete parts or any combination of those.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The maser is a non-electronic microwave amplifier.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Instrument amplifiers are a range of audio power amplifiers used to increase the sound level of musical instruments, for example guitars, during performances.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] An amplifier's tone mainly comes from the order and amount in which it applies EQ and distortion.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] These amplifiers are used to amplify the voice of a person with watts, Examples are Megaphones, Microphones, personal amplifiers, etc.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] They are used for sporting events, schools, construction, and fire and safety.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] One set of classifications for amplifiers is based on which device terminal is common to both the input and the output circuit.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In the case of bipolar junction transistors, the three classes are common emitter, common base, and common collector.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] For field-effect transistors, the corresponding configurations are common source, common gate, and common drain; for vacuum tubes, common cathode, common grid, and common plate.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The common emitter (or common source, common cathode, etc.) is most often configured to provide amplification of a voltage applied between base and emitter, and the output signal taken between collector and emitter is inverted, relative to the input.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The common collector arrangement applies the input voltage between base and collector, and to take the output voltage between emitter and collector.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] This causes negative feedback, and the output voltage tends to follow the input voltage.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] This arrangement is also used as the input presents a high impedance and does not load the signal source, though the voltage amplification is less than one.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The common-collector circuit is, therefore, better known as an emitter follower, source follower, or cathode follower.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] An amplifier whose output exhibits no feedback to its input side is described as 'unilateral'.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The input impedance of a unilateral amplifier is independent of load, and output impedance is independent of signal source impedance.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] An amplifier that uses feedback to connect part of the output back to the input is a *bilateral* amplifier.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Bilateral amplifier input impedance depends on the load, and output impedance on the signal source impedance.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] All amplifiers are bilateral to some degree; however they may often be modeled as unilateral under operating conditions where feedback is small enough to neglect for most purposes, simplifying analysis (see the common base article for an example).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Another way to classify amplifiers is by the phase relationship of the input signal to the output signal.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] An 'inverting' amplifier produces an output 180 degrees out of phase with the input signal (that is, a polarity inversion or mirror image of the input as seen on an oscilloscope).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] A 'non-inverting' amplifier maintains the phase of the input signal waveforms.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] An emitter follower is a type of non-inverting amplifier, indicating that the signal at the emitter of a transistor is following (that is, matching with unity gain but perhaps an offset) the input signal.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Voltage follower is also non-inverting type of amplifier having unity gain.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] This description can apply to a single stage of an amplifier, or to a complete amplifier system.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Other amplifiers may be classified by their function or output characteristics.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] These functional descriptions usually apply to complete amplifier systems or sub-systems and rarely to individual stages.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Amplifiers are sometimes classified by the coupling method of the signal at the input, output, or between stages.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] By design these amplifiers cannot amplify DC signals as the capacitors block the DC component of the input signal.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] RC-coupled amplifiers were used very often in circuits with vacuum tubes or discrete transistors.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In the days of the integrated circuit a few more transistors on a chip are much cheaper and smaller than a capacitor.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] This kind of amplifier is most often used in selective radio-frequency circuits.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Quite often LC-coupled and transformer-coupled amplifiers cannot be distinguished as a transformer is some kind of inductor.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] This class of amplifier was very uncommon in the vacuum tube days when the anode (output) voltage was at greater than several hundred volts and the grid (input) voltage at a few volts minus.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] So they were used only if the gain was specified down to DC (e.g., in an oscilloscope).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In the context of modern electronics developers are encouraged to use directly coupled amplifiers whenever possible.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In FET and CMOS technologies direct coupling is dominant since gates of MOSFETs theoretically pass no current through themselves.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Therefore, DC component of the input signals is automatically filtered.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Depending on the frequency range and other properties amplifiers are designed according to different principles.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Amplifiers that operate down to DC are used only when direct-current response is needed.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Amplifiers for direct current signals are vulnerable to minor variations in the properties of components with time.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Special methods, such as chopper stabilized amplifiers are used to prevent objectionable drift in the amplifier's properties for DC.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] "DC-blocking" capacitors can be added to remove DC and sub-sonic frequencies from audio amplifiers.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Amplifiers are designed according to different principles depending on their frequency range and other properties.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] As soon as any connection within the circuit gets longer than perhaps 1% of the wavelength of the highest specified frequency (e.g., at 100 MHz the wavelength is 3 m, so the critical connection length is approx.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] 3 cm) design properties radically change.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] For example, a specified length and width of a PCB trace can be used as a selective or impedance-matching entity.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Above a few hundred MHz, it gets difficult to use discrete elements, especially inductors.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In most cases, PCB traces of very closely defined shapes are used instead (stripline techniques).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The practical amplifier circuit shown above could be the basis for a moderate-power audio amplifier.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] It features a typical (though substantially simplified) design as found in modern amplifiers, with a class-AB push–pull output stage, and uses some overall negative feedback.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Bipolar transistors are shown, but this design would also be realizable with FETs or valves.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The input signal is coupled through capacitor C1 to the base of transistor Q1.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The capacitor allows the AC signal to pass, but blocks the DC bias voltage established by resistors R1 and R2 so that any preceding circuit is not affected by it.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Q1 and Q2 form a differential amplifier (an amplifier that multiplies the difference between two inputs by some constant), in an arrangement known as a long-tailed pair.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] This arrangement is used to conveniently allow the use of negative feedback, which is fed from the output to Q2 via R7 and R8.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The negative feedback into the difference amplifier allows the amplifier to compare the input to the actual output.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The amplified signal from Q1 is directly fed to the second stage, Q3, which is a common emitter stage that provides further amplification of the signal and the DC bias for the output stages, Q4 and Q5.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] R6 provides the load for Q3 (a better design would probably use some form of active load here, such as a constant-current sink).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] So far, all of the amplifier is operating in class A.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The output pair are arranged in class-AB push–pull, also called a complementary pair.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] They provide the majority of the current amplification (while consuming low quiescent current) and directly drive the load, connected via DC-blocking capacitor C2.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The diodes D1 and D2 provide a small amount of constant voltage bias for the output pair, just biasing them into the conducting state so that crossover distortion is minimized.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] That is, the diodes push the output stage firmly into class-AB mode (assuming that the base-emitter drop of the output transistors is reduced by heat dissipation).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] This design is simple, but a good basis for a practical design because it automatically stabilises its operating point, since feedback internally operates from DC up through the audio range and beyond.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Further circuit elements would probably be found in a real design that would roll-off the frequency response above the needed range to prevent the possibility of unwanted oscillation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] A common solution to help stabilise the output devices is to include some emitter resistors, typically one ohm or so.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Calculating the values of the circuit's resistors and capacitors is done based on the components employed and the intended use of the amp.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Any real amplifier is an imperfect realization of an ideal amplifier.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] An important limitation of a real amplifier is that the output it generates is ultimately limited by the power available from the power supply.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] An amplifier saturates and clips the output if the input signal becomes too large for the amplifier to reproduce or exceeds operational limits for the device.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The power supply may influence the output, so must be considered in the design.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The power output from an amplifier cannot exceed its input power.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The amplifier circuit has an "open loop" performance.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] This is described by various parameters (gain, slew rate, output impedance, distortion, bandwidth, signal-to-noise ratio, etc.).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Many modern amplifiers use negative feedback techniques to hold the gain at the desired value and reduce distortion.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Negative loop feedback has the intended effect of lowering the output impedance and thereby increasing electrical damping of loudspeaker motion at and near the resonance frequency of the speaker.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] When assessing rated amplifier power output, it is useful to consider the applied load, the signal type (e.g., speech or music), required power output duration (i.e., short-time or continuous), and required dynamic range (e.g., recorded or live audio).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] In high-powered audio applications that require long cables to the load (e.g., cinemas and shopping centres) it may be more efficient to connect to the load at line output voltage, with matching transformers at source and loads.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] This avoids long runs of heavy speaker cables.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] To prevent instability or overheating requires care to ensure solid state amplifiers are adequately loaded.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Most have a rated minimum load impedance.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] All amplifiers generate heat through electrical losses.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] The amplifier must dissipate this heat via convection or forced air cooling.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Heat can damage or reduce electronic component service life.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Designers and installers must also consider heating effects on adjacent equipment.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Different power supply types result in many different methods of bias.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Bias is a technique by which active devices are set to operate in a particular region, or by which the DC component of the output signal is set to the midpoint between the maximum voltages available from the power supply.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Most amplifiers use several devices at each stage; they are typically matched in specifications except for polarity.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Matched inverted polarity devices are called complementary pairs.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Class-A amplifiers generally use only one device, unless the power supply is set to provide both positive and negative voltages, in which case a dual device symmetrical design may be used.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Class-C amplifiers, by definition, use a single polarity supply.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Amplifiers often have multiple stages in cascade to increase gain.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] Each stage of these designs may be a different type of amp to suit the needs of that stage.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/amplifier] For instance, the first stage might be a class-A stage, feeding a class-AB push–pull second stage, which then drives a class-G final output stage, taking advantage of the strengths of each type, while minimizing their weaknesses.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Both human-made and natural sources generate changing electrical currents and voltages that can cause EMI: ignition systems, cellular network of mobile phones, lightning, solar flares, and auroras (northern/southern lights).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] It can also affect mobile phones, FM radios, and televisions, as well as observations for radio astronomy and atmospheric science.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] EMI can be used intentionally for radio jamming, as in electronic warfare.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Since the earliest days of radio communications, the negative effects of interference from both intentional and unintentional transmissions have been felt and the need to manage the radio frequency spectrum became apparent.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] In 1933, a meeting of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in Paris recommended the International Special Committee on Radio Interference (CISPR) be set up to deal with the emerging problem of EMI.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] CISPR subsequently produced technical publications covering measurement and test techniques and recommended emission and immunity limits.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] These have evolved over the decades and form the basis of much of the world's EMC regulations today.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] In 1979, legal limits were imposed on electromagnetic emissions from all digital equipment by the FCC in the US in response to the increased number of digital systems that were interfering with wired and radio communications.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Test methods and limits were based on CISPR publications, although similar limits were already enforced in parts of Europe.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] In the mid 1980s, the European Union member states adopted a number of "new approach" directives with the intention of standardizing technical requirements for products so that they do not become a barrier to trade within the EC.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] One of these was the EMC Directive (89/336/EC) and it applies to all equipment placed on the market or taken into service.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Its scope covers all apparatus "liable to cause electromagnetic disturbance or the performance of which is liable to be affected by such disturbance".
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] This was the first time there was a legal requirement on immunity, as well as emissions on apparatus intended for the general population.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Although there may be additional costs involved for some products to give them a known level of immunity, it increases their perceived quality as they are able to co-exist with apparatus in the active EM environment of modern times and with fewer problems.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Many countries now have similar requirements for products to meet some level of electromagnetic compatibility (EMC) regulation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Electromagnetic interference divides into several categories according to the source and signal characteristics.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] The origin of interference, often called "noise" in this context, can be human-made (artificial) or natural.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Continuous, or continuous wave (CW), interference arises where the source continuously emits at a given range of frequencies.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] This type is naturally divided into sub-categories according to frequency range, and as a whole is sometimes referred to as "DC to daylight".
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] One common classification is into narrowband and broadband, according to the spread of the frequency range.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] An electromagnetic pulse (EMP), sometimes called a transient disturbance, arises where the source emits a short-duration pulse of energy.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] The energy is usually broadband by nature, although it often excites a relatively narrow-band *damped sine wave* response in the victim.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Sources divide broadly into isolated and repetitive events.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Conducted electromagnetic interference is caused by the physical contact of the conductors as opposed to radiated EMI, which is caused by induction (without physical contact of the conductors).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Electromagnetic disturbances in the EM field of a conductor will no longer be confined to the surface of the conductor and will radiate away from it.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] This persists in all conductors and mutual inductance between two radiated electromagnetic fields will result in EMI.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Some of the technical terms which are employed can be used with differing meanings.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Some phenomena may be referred to by various different terms.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] These terms are used here in a widely accepted way, which is consistent with other articles in the encyclopedia.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] The basic arrangement of noise emitter or source, coupling path and victim, receptor or sink is shown in the figure below.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Source and victim are usually electronic hardware devices, though the source may be a natural phenomenon such as a lightning strike, electrostatic discharge (ESD) or, in one famous case, the Big Bang at the origin of the Universe.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] There are four basic coupling mechanisms: conductive, capacitive, magnetic or inductive, and radiative.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Any coupling path can be broken down into one or more of these coupling mechanisms working together.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] For example the lower path in the diagram involves inductive, conductive and capacitive modes.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Conductive coupling occurs when the coupling path between the source and victim is formed by direct electrical contact with a conducting body, for example a transmission line, wire, cable, PCB trace or metal enclosure.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Inductive coupling occurs where the source and victim are separated by a short distance (typically less than a wavelength).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Strictly, "Inductive coupling" can be of two kinds, electrical induction and magnetic induction.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] It is common to refer to electrical induction as *capacitive coupling*, and to magnetic induction as *inductive coupling*.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Capacitive coupling occurs when a varying electrical field exists between two adjacent conductors typically less than a wavelength apart, inducing a change in voltage on the receiving conductor.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Inductive coupling or magnetic coupling occurs when a varying magnetic field exists between two parallel conductors typically less than a wavelength apart, inducing a change in voltage along the receiving conductor.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Radiative coupling or electromagnetic coupling occurs when source and victim are separated by a large distance, typically more than a wavelength.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Source and victim act as radio antennas: the source emits or radiates an electromagnetic wave which propagates across the space in between and is picked up or received by the victim.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] This is also a definition used by the frequency administration to provide frequency assignments and assignment of frequency channels to radio stations or systems, as well as to analyze electromagnetic compatibility between radiocommunication services.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Conducted EMI is caused by the physical contact of the conductors as opposed to radiated EMI which is caused by induction (without physical contact of the conductors).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] For lower frequencies, EMI is caused by conduction and, for higher frequencies, by radiation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] EMI through the ground wire is also very common in an electrical facility.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Interference tends to be more troublesome with older radio technologies such as analogue amplitude modulation, which have no way of distinguishing unwanted in-band signals from the intended signal, and the omnidirectional antennas used with broadcast systems.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Newer radio systems incorporate several improvements that enhance the selectivity.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] In digital radio systems, such as Wi-Fi, error-correction techniques can be used.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Spread-spectrum and frequency-hopping techniques can be used with both analogue and digital signalling to improve resistance to interference.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] A highly directional receiver, such as a parabolic antenna or a diversity receiver, can be used to select one signal in space to the exclusion of others.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] The most extreme example of digital spread-spectrum signalling to date is ultra-wideband (UWB), which proposes the use of large sections of the radio spectrum at low amplitudes to transmit high-bandwidth digital data.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] In the United States, the 1982 Public Law 97-259 allowed the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to regulate the susceptibility of consumer electronic equipment.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Potential sources of RFI and EMI include: various types of transmitters, doorbell transformers, toaster ovens, electric blankets, ultrasonic pest control devices, electric bug zappers, heating pads, and touch controlled lamps.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Multiple CRT computer monitors or televisions sitting too close to one another can sometimes cause a "shimmy" effect in each other, due to the electromagnetic nature of their picture tubes, especially when one of their de-gaussing coils is activated.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Electromagnetic interference at 2.4 GHz may be caused by 802.11b, 802.11g and 802.11n wireless devices, Bluetooth devices, baby monitors and cordless telephones, video senders, and microwave ovens.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Switching loads (inductive, capacitive, and resistive), such as electric motors, transformers, heaters, lamps, ballast, power supplies, etc., all cause electromagnetic interference especially at currents above 2 A.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] The usual method used for suppressing EMI is by connecting a snubber network, a resistor in series with a capacitor, across a pair of contacts.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] While this may offer modest EMI reduction at very low currents, snubbers do not work at currents over 2 A with electromechanical contacts.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Another method for suppressing EMI is the use of ferrite core noise suppressors (or ferrite beads), which are inexpensive and which clip on to the power lead of the offending device or the compromised device.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Switched-mode power supplies can be a source of EMI, but have become less of a problem as design techniques have improved, such as integrated power factor correction.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Most countries have legal requirements that mandate electromagnetic compatibility: electronic and electrical hardware must still work correctly when subjected to certain amounts of EMI, and should not emit EMI, which could interfere with other equipment (such as radios).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Radio frequency signal quality has declined throughout the 21st century by roughly one decibel per year as the spectrum becomes increasingly crowded.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] This has inflicted a Red Queen's race on the mobile phone industry as companies have been forced to put up more cellular towers (at new frequencies) that then cause more interference thereby requiring more investment by the providers and frequent upgrades of mobile phones to match.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] These are civilian standards for domestic, commercial, industrial and automotive sectors.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] These standards form the basis of other national or regional standards, most notably the European Norms (EN) written by CENELEC (European committee for electrotechnical standardisation).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] US organizations include the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), the American National Standards Institute (ANSI), and the US Military (MILSTD).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Integrated circuits are often a source of EMI, but they must usually couple their energy to larger objects such as heatsinks, circuit board planes and cables to radiate significantly.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] On integrated circuits, important means of reducing EMI are: the use of bypass or decoupling capacitors on each active device (connected across the power supply, as close to the device as possible), rise time control of high-speed signals using series resistors, and IC power supply pin filtering.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Shielding is usually a last resort after other techniques have failed, because of the added expense of shielding components such as conductive gaskets.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] At lower frequencies, such as 133 MHz, radiation is almost exclusively via I/O cables; RF noise gets onto the power planes and is coupled to the line drivers via the VCC and GND pins.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] The RF is then coupled to the cable through the line driver as common-mode noise.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Since the noise is common-mode, shielding has very little effect, even with differential pairs.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] The RF energy is capacitively coupled from the signal pair to the shield and the shield itself does the radiating.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] One cure for this is to use a braid-breaker or choke to reduce the common-mode signal.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] At higher frequencies, usually above 500 MHz, traces get electrically longer and higher above the plane.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Two techniques are used at these frequencies: wave shaping with series resistors and embedding the traces between the two planes.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] If all these measures still leave too much EMI, shielding such as RF gaskets and copper or conductive tape can be used.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Most digital equipment is designed with metal or conductive-coated plastic cases.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Any unshielded semiconductor (e.g. an integrated circuit) will tend to act as a detector for those radio signals commonly found in the domestic environment (e.g. mobile phones).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Such a detector can demodulate the high frequency mobile phone carrier (e.g., GSM850 and GSM1900, GSM900 and GSM1800) and produce low-frequency (e.g., 217 Hz) demodulated signals.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] This demodulation manifests itself as unwanted audible buzz in audio appliances such as microphone amplifier, speaker amplifier, car radio, telephones etc.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Adding onboard EMI filters or special layout techniques can help in bypassing EMI or improving RF immunity.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Some ICs are designed (e.g., LMV831-LMV834, MAX9724) to have integrated RF filters or a special design that helps reduce any demodulation of high-frequency carrier.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Designers often need to carry out special tests for RF immunity of parts to be used in a system.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] These tests are often done in an anechoic chamber with a controlled RF environment where the test vectors produce a RF field similar to that produced in an actual environment.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Interference in radio astronomy, where it is commonly referred to as radio-frequency interference (RFI), is any source of transmission that is within the observed frequency band other than the celestial sources themselves.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Because transmitters on and around the Earth can be many times stronger than the astronomical signal of interest, RFI is a major concern for performing radio astronomy.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Some of the frequency bands that are very important for radio astronomy, such as the 21-cm HI line at 1420 MHz, are protected by regulation.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] However, modern radio-astronomical observatories such as VLA, LOFAR, and ALMA have a very large bandwidth over which they can observe.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Techniques to deal with RFI range from filters in hardware to advanced algorithms in software.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] One way to deal with strong transmitters is to filter out the frequency of the source completely.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] This is for example the case for the LOFAR observatory, which filters out the FM radio stations between 90 and 110 MHz.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] It is important to remove such strong sources of interference as soon as possible, because they might "saturate" the highly sensitive receivers (amplifiers and analogue-to-digital converters), which means that the received signal is stronger than the receiver can handle.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] However, filtering out a frequency band implies that these frequencies can never be observed with the instrument.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] A common technique to deal with RFI within the observed frequency bandwidth, is to employ RFI detection in software.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Such software can find samples in time, frequency or time-frequency space that are contaminated by an interfering source.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] These samples are subsequently ignored in further analysis of the observed data.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] This process is often referred to as *data flagging*.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Because most transmitters have a small bandwidth and are not continuously present such as lightning or citizens' band (CB) radio devices, most of the data remains available for the astronomical analysis.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] However, data flagging can not solve issues with continuous broad-band transmitters, such as windmills, digital video or digital audio transmitters.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Another way to manage RFI is to establish a radio quiet zone (RQZ).
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] RQZ is a well-defined area surrounding receivers that has special regulations to reduce RFI in favor of radio astronomy observations within the zone.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] The regulations may include special management of spectrum and power flux or power flux-density limitations.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] The controls within the zone may cover elements other than radio transmitters or radio devices.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] These include aircraft controls and control of unintentional radiators such as industrial, scientific and medical devices, vehicles, and power lines.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] The first RQZ for radio astronomy is United States National Radio Quiet Zone (NRQZ), established in 1958.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Prior to the introduction of Wi-Fi, one of the biggest applications of 5 GHz band was the Terminal Doppler Weather Radar.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] The decision to use 5 GHz spectrum for Wi-Fi was finalized at the World Radiocommunication Conference in 2003; however, meteorological authorities were not involved in the process.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] The subsequent lax implementation and misconfiguration of DFS had caused significant disruption in weather radar operations in a number of countries around the world.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] In Hungary, the weather radar system was declared non-operational for more than a month.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Due to the severity of interference, South African weather services ended up abandoning C band operation, switching their radar network to S band.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Transmissions on adjacent bands to those used by passive remote sensing, such as weather satellites, have caused interference, sometimes significant.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] There is concern that adoption of insufficiently regulated 5G could produce major interference issues.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] Significant interference can impair numerical weather prediction performance and incur negative economic and public safety impacts.
[src:electromagnetic-interference/electromagnetic-interference] These concerns led US Secretary of Commerce Wilbur Ross and NASA Administrator Jim Bridenstine in February 2019 to urge the FCC to cancel a proposed spectrum auction, which was rejected.
